## Introduction @unplugged

Everyone loves a good joke.   
Let's build one we can share with friends. 

Making a joke (or a short story) in Arcade is a lot like creating a greeting card. 
You can use your background and sprites to convey a sense of emotion and 
add style. 

![Here's the story](/static/skillmaps/clicker/saltwater.gif "Why do tropical fish like saltwater?" )

## Step 1

The code for a greeting card (with text) is already in the workspace. 
You can build from this to create a joke.

To prepare for the next steps, 
[__*click here to choose a joke from our list*__](#doc:/reference/joke-examples "Find a good two line joke here."),
 or create your own!

```hint
Q: Why do tropical fish swim in saltwater?
A: Because pepper makes them sneeze!

```


## Step 2


Do you have your joke?

 Now design your scene 

---

 Locate the ``||scene: set background image to [ ]||`` block and click 
inside the grey square to open the image editor. 

 Create a background that shows where your joke takes place.  
Is it the ocean? The sky? A kitchen? 

[__*(learn about background scenes...)*__](#doc:/reference/add-background-ref "Learn to add a background.")

## Step 4

One benefit of having text controlled by a button is that
the reader gets to choose the timing of the joke. 

No matter how you split your joke, you're likely to get the biggest laugh if
your punchline is presented separately at the end. 

---

 Write your joke on paper and circle the punchline. It's usually 
the last line, and it's the part that makes people laugh.

 Enter your punchline into the last ``||game: show long text [" "] [bottom]||``
block inside your **on button pressed** container,
and split the rest of the joke into other text blocks above it. 

 If your joke has two characters, you'll probably want to use the 
``||sprites: [mySprite] say [":)"]||`` block instead so people can tell who's talking.

[__*(learn different ways to display text...)*__](#doc  "Learn more about game text.")

``` block
    game.showLongText("If at first you don't succeed...", DialogLayout.Bottom)
    game.showLongText("...you shouldn't try skydiving!", DialogLayout.Bottom)
```
or 

```block
let mySprite: Sprite = null;
let mySprite2: Sprite = null;
mySprite.say("If at first you don't succeed...")
mySprite2.say("...you shouldn't try skydiving!")

```


## Step 5

Take a minute to check your joke in the simulator!

Is it funny?  Does the text overlap anything important on the screen?

---

  Experiement with the location of the text by changing the location to
the **top**, **left**, or **right** in the 
``||game: show long text [" "] [bottom]||`` block. 

Does the text flow better somewhere else?

``` block
    game.showLongText("If at first you don't succeed...", DialogLayout.Top)
    game.showLongText("...you shouldn't try skydiving!", DialogLayout.Right)
```

## Step 6

 Now take a bow 

End on a high note with confetti or a screen full of smiles.

---

 Move the ``||scene: start screen [confetti] effect||`` block out of the
**on start** container and into the end of the **on button pressed** container.

 Change **confetti** to whatever gives your joke the biggest punch!

```blocks

controller.A.onEvent(ControllerButtonEvent.Pressed, function () {
    game.showLongText("Why do tropical fish swim in saltwater?", DialogLayout.Top)
    game.showLongText("Because, pepper makes them sneeze!", DialogLayout.Bottom)
    effects.bubbles.startScreenEffect()
})

```
